WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.120
ADI HADDAD: I'm Adi.

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:02.380
I'm Games video manager.

00:00:02.380 --> 00:00:03.550
I'm based in Tel Aviv.

00:00:03.550 --> 00:00:06.220
And I work with Israel and
Turkish gaming companies.

00:00:06.220 --> 00:00:10.520
And I camp and I win
games because of that.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:13.150
So let's start with a question.

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:15.580
By raise of hands, who
wants to make more money

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:16.720
from their games?

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:17.900
Raise your hands.

00:00:17.900 --> 00:00:18.400
Yeah.

00:00:18.400 --> 00:00:22.330
That makes sense because
you're here today.

00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:23.770
And the obvious
follow up question

00:00:23.770 --> 00:00:28.150
should be, how can you make
more money from your games?

00:00:28.150 --> 00:00:30.420
Harry Markowitz, a Nobel
Prize winning economist,

00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:33.790
said he would never be 100%
invested in stocks, or bonds,

00:00:33.790 --> 00:00:36.460
or cash, basically
saying he will never

00:00:36.460 --> 00:00:39.230
put all his eggs in one basket.

00:00:39.230 --> 00:00:41.540
And when you think about
it, why mobile games should

00:00:41.540 --> 00:00:43.290
be any different?

00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:44.910
Why rely on one
source of revenue

00:00:44.910 --> 00:00:49.100
and not try to diversify
your revenue streams?

00:00:49.100 --> 00:00:52.388
In our industry it's set
up in a very unique way.

00:00:52.388 --> 00:00:54.680
Usually the game genres
determine the game monetization

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:55.480
you have.

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:59.120
So in hyper casual games, we
usually see ad monetization.

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:03.200
In RPG and strategy games,
we usually IP monetization.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:04.777
And this isn't a bad thing.

00:01:04.777 --> 00:01:06.860
But today I wanted to take
a step back and rethink

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:08.570
this assumption.

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:10.550
Ask yourself, does
that make sense

00:01:10.550 --> 00:01:13.480
to focus on one monetization
strategy in your games?

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:15.290
And what can you learn
from other genres?

00:01:15.290 --> 00:01:19.580
And what can you learn
from other developers?

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:22.530
So today I'm going to talk
about why diversify monetization

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:24.560
strategies in mobile games.

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:26.310
Then I'm going to
discuss different trends

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:28.857
around this topic.

00:01:28.857 --> 00:01:30.690
And then I'm going to
finish with Gram Games

00:01:30.690 --> 00:01:32.970
on stage who are going to
share with us their journey

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:36.180
of revenue diversification.

00:01:36.180 --> 00:01:39.750
So why diversify?

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:42.330
As Markowitz said, by
diversifying revenue streams,

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:44.790
you're actually decreasing
the risk you have in games.

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:46.498
But more than that,
you have more options

00:01:46.498 --> 00:01:48.000
to monetize your
audience, which can

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.620
create an uplift in revenue.

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:53.180
Another reason is based
on the Google Play data.

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:56.030
And it's actually the first time
we are showing that on stage.

00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:57.890
So let's take a look.

00:01:57.890 --> 00:02:00.290
What you see in the
graph in the x-axis

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:02.930
is the percentage of
revenue coming from top 5%

00:02:02.930 --> 00:02:05.150
of spenders in the game.

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:07.640
What you see in the
y-axis is the reactivation

00:02:07.640 --> 00:02:09.889
rate of churn
bias, or how likely

00:02:09.889 --> 00:02:13.555
is the game to get
back churn bias.

00:02:13.555 --> 00:02:14.180
Take a picture.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:15.230
That's a good one.

00:02:15.230 --> 00:02:17.755
And what we found
out in our data

00:02:17.755 --> 00:02:19.880
that we actually have a
correlation between the two

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:21.030
things.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:23.190
So if you look at the
bottom right corner,

00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:25.607
you see that games that are
really concentrated on revenue

00:02:25.607 --> 00:02:28.490
from the top 5% of spenders
they have are actually less

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:31.010
likely to get back churn bias.

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:33.320
On the other hand, if you
look at the top left corner,

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.380
on the star sign,
you see that games

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:36.880
that are really
good at getting back

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:40.040
churn buyers are less dependent
on the top 5% of spenders

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:42.710
they have.

00:02:42.710 --> 00:02:45.590
So what that means is that
trying to get $1 from a larger

00:02:45.590 --> 00:02:48.110
audience is actually more
sustainable in trying to get

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:49.740
$100 from a high value user.

00:02:53.227 --> 00:02:55.060
so what trends do we
see around monetization

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:57.570
and diversification?

00:02:57.570 --> 00:02:59.850
Subscriptions,
rewarded ads, and IAP.

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:03.030
So subscription is quite
new in mobile games.

00:03:03.030 --> 00:03:05.102
But rewarded ads and
IAP are not new per se.

00:03:05.102 --> 00:03:06.810
We saw some interesting
trends with them.

00:03:06.810 --> 00:03:08.830
And we are going to
discuss that later.

00:03:08.830 --> 00:03:10.720
But let's start
with subscriptions.

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:12.870
So who is using
subscriptions in the games.

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:14.260
Please raise your hand.

00:03:14.260 --> 00:03:14.760
OK.

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:14.970
Yeah.

00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:15.540
A few hands.

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:17.093
That makes sense.

00:03:17.093 --> 00:03:19.260
And subscription is not a
foreign concept in gaming.

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:20.677
We've seen that
on PC and console.

00:03:20.677 --> 00:03:23.412
But it's actually quite a
new concept in mobile games.

00:03:23.412 --> 00:03:24.870
And we see more
and more developers

00:03:24.870 --> 00:03:26.850
who are using this
strategy on top of the IAP

00:03:26.850 --> 00:03:29.190
they have in their game in
order to create the premium

00:03:29.190 --> 00:03:31.758
experience for users.

00:03:31.758 --> 00:03:34.050
And actually, on Google Play
we see a growing momentum,

00:03:34.050 --> 00:03:36.240
with more than 70%
year on year growth

00:03:36.240 --> 00:03:37.500
in subscribers and games.

00:03:40.117 --> 00:03:41.700
And developers are
using this strategy

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:44.980
and reporting different
benefits of doing so.

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:48.010
So [INAUDIBLE],, for example,
reported that subscribers

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:50.540
pay 20% more than they used to.

00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:53.090
And Scopely reported that
subscribers have much higher

00:03:53.090 --> 00:03:53.590
LTV.

00:03:56.140 --> 00:03:58.053
And another reason of
using subscriptions

00:03:58.053 --> 00:03:59.720
is that it can actually
help you diffuse

00:03:59.720 --> 00:04:01.900
the feeling of regrets in game.

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:04.270
So what happens sometimes
is that users binge on IAP,

00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:06.190
and then they feel
regret doing so.

00:04:06.190 --> 00:04:08.870
But if you use subscriptions,
you can actually change that.

00:04:08.870 --> 00:04:11.290
So instead of eating all the
Halloween candies in one day,

00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:15.020
user will eat one candy each
day for a long period of time.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:18.790
And then they feel
rested while doing so.

00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:21.930
So how to design
subscription experience?

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:24.030
So that's something that
requires a mindset shift.

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:26.760
You can use your IAP SKUs,
repackage them, and offer them

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:28.020
as subscription bundles.

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:29.460
It can actually work for you.

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:31.833
But we think that you
can do more than that.

00:04:31.833 --> 00:04:34.000
But while IAP is more about
the ownership of things,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.470
users are paying to own and
keep something in the game,

00:04:36.470 --> 00:04:39.600
subscription is more about the
access to a premium experience,

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:43.190
access users can
gain and also lose.

00:04:43.190 --> 00:04:46.373
And you have two main use cases
for subscriptions in games.

00:04:46.373 --> 00:04:48.540
The first one is to convert
new buyers often looking

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:49.630
for really good deals.

00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:51.585
So if you take a
look at the example,

00:04:51.585 --> 00:04:54.450
see that Scopely on
top of the IAP deal

00:04:54.450 --> 00:04:56.550
are offering really
exclusive rewards, like loss

00:04:56.550 --> 00:04:59.012
protection in the game,
and also higher data caps.

00:04:59.012 --> 00:05:01.470
And they're offering this bundle
very early on in the game,

00:05:01.470 --> 00:05:03.678
just after a first
time user experience.

00:05:03.678 --> 00:05:06.220
And the idea behind that is they
are trying to also make sure

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.040
that new buyers will
stay longer in the game

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:09.082
and play longer sessions.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:15.970
And second use case
for a subscription

00:05:15.970 --> 00:05:19.250
is to create a loyalty program
for your most valuable users.

00:05:19.250 --> 00:05:21.745
So these users are often looking
for a premium experience,

00:05:21.745 --> 00:05:23.620
rewards for the commitment
they have to game,

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:26.220
and also a prestige feeling.

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:28.480
And in the examples
[INAUDIBLE] for the VIP

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:30.370
users are offering quite a lot.

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:32.590
Extra currency,
exclusive tournaments,

00:05:32.590 --> 00:05:35.303
early access to new content, and
access to a special durables.

00:05:35.303 --> 00:05:36.220
So that's quite a lot.

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:42.260
So that was subscriptions.

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:44.925
And let's move to rewarded ads.

00:05:44.925 --> 00:05:45.800
So is it a new trend?

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:47.850
You are obviously
asking yourself

00:05:47.850 --> 00:05:49.350
why I'm speaking
about rewarded ads.

00:05:49.350 --> 00:05:51.710
So it's not a new
monetization model.

00:05:51.710 --> 00:05:54.097
We've seen that for a
couple of years now.

00:05:54.097 --> 00:05:56.180
But what the Google Ad Mob
team found out recently

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:59.480
in the research they did is
that IP heavy developers who

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:01.820
didn't focus on ads
before are starting

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:04.388
to rethink the monetization
strategy they have in games.

00:06:04.388 --> 00:06:05.930
And as a result,
they're implementing

00:06:05.930 --> 00:06:07.523
more and more rewarded ads.

00:06:07.523 --> 00:06:09.440
And that's why you see
more hybrid games today

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:11.630
in the industry, in
both IAP and rewarded

00:06:11.630 --> 00:06:12.770
ads implemented in them.

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:16.660
So why use rewarded ads?

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:19.460
So we have a couple
of reasons for that.

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:22.090
First of all, you can
monetize your non-paying users

00:06:22.090 --> 00:06:23.435
with rewarded ads.

00:06:23.435 --> 00:06:25.060
You actually give
your users the option

00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:27.550
to choose the currency they
would like to pay with,

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:30.180
time or money.

00:06:30.180 --> 00:06:31.680
It can also increase
your engagement

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:33.552
in the game of both
payers and non payers.

00:06:33.552 --> 00:06:35.760
Users are getting back more
frequently into the game,

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:37.010
and also play longer sessions.

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:43.445
And the third key reason
of using rewarded ads--

00:06:43.445 --> 00:06:45.070
and you may not be
familiar with that--

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:48.620
is that it can actually predict
IAP conversion in games.

00:06:48.620 --> 00:06:51.070
So what Kongregate found
out recently in their games

00:06:51.070 --> 00:06:54.160
is that new users who watch an
ad in the first ever session

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:56.020
they're having in
the game are actually

00:06:56.020 --> 00:06:58.300
much more likely to
make an in-app purchase.

00:06:58.300 --> 00:07:00.840
And they saw an uptick
of between 250% to 500%

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:03.230
in that conversion rate,
which is really amazing.

00:07:06.990 --> 00:07:08.960
So how to design a
rewarded ads experience?

00:07:08.960 --> 00:07:10.790
We know it can be a bit tricky.

00:07:10.790 --> 00:07:12.890
So we're showing you an
Ad Mob framework that

00:07:12.890 --> 00:07:14.750
can help you in the process.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:16.250
So you need to think
about placement

00:07:16.250 --> 00:07:20.232
of the ads, user targeting,
cadence, and measurement.

00:07:22.545 --> 00:07:24.170
And let's see what
Kongregate are doing

00:07:24.170 --> 00:07:26.370
for each one of these points.

00:07:26.370 --> 00:07:29.540
So first of all, the ads should
be part of a game economy

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:31.310
design, and should
give something

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:32.752
meaningful to your users.

00:07:32.752 --> 00:07:35.210
But at the same time, make sure
it doesn't compete directly

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:37.890
with your IAP.

00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:39.900
And every user should
have access to the ads.

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:42.450
But if you decide to remove
this access to paying users,

00:07:42.450 --> 00:07:46.200
don't forget to give
them their rewards.

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:48.000
And more is not always better.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.570
They found out that between six
to eight ads per user per day

00:07:51.570 --> 00:07:54.620
is the best practice.

00:07:54.620 --> 00:07:57.220
And lastly, don't forget to
measure important metrics,

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:59.720
like ad viewership
and frequency,

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:01.730
because you can segment
your users with that,

00:08:01.730 --> 00:08:03.950
and optimize the
performance of each segment.

00:08:07.190 --> 00:08:07.690
OK.

00:08:07.690 --> 00:08:10.700
So let's talk about
IAP a little bit.

00:08:10.700 --> 00:08:14.650
So what we see with IAP
is very similar to what

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:16.135
we see with rewarded ads.

00:08:16.135 --> 00:08:17.650
An increasing
number of developers

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:20.620
who didn't focus on IAP
before and really focus on ads

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:23.290
are starting to
shift that focus.

00:08:23.290 --> 00:08:25.690
And they're either implementing
IAP in existing titles,

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:28.420
or started to develop new IAP
based games for the first time.

00:08:30.918 --> 00:08:33.376
Tapps Games, for example, a
Brazilian company, really known

00:08:33.376 --> 00:08:36.350
for hyper casual games,
decided to double down

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:38.392
IAP in the "Bid Wars"
titles, which are

00:08:38.392 --> 00:08:39.559
auction like strategy games.

00:08:39.559 --> 00:08:40.945
Rally nice games.

00:08:40.945 --> 00:08:43.070
And they've been working
very closely with the Play

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:44.700
team in their time on that.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:47.770
And in less than two years, they
saw an uptick of more than 200%

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:48.770
in IP revenue.

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:51.703
So that was a game
changer for the company.

00:08:51.703 --> 00:08:54.245
And as a result, IAP today is
part of the company's strategy.

00:08:57.825 --> 00:09:01.940
So why developers are looking
to diversify with IAP?

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:04.010
So first of all,
successful IAP games

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:06.320
can be mentioned and developed
by really small teams,

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.540
and simple operation
for structures.

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:10.173
In some cases,
we're seeing teams

00:09:10.173 --> 00:09:12.590
as small as 10 people who are
responsible for multimillion

00:09:12.590 --> 00:09:15.100
success stories.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:18.370
IAP games also rely less on
massive number of installs.

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:20.580
So instead of focusing
on game launches,

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:23.170
they're actually shifting focus
to more long term sustainable

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:26.470
KPIs, like game engagement.

00:09:26.470 --> 00:09:28.360
And IAP games are also
all about taking back

00:09:28.360 --> 00:09:30.220
control of your own
revenue, instead of

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:33.552
depending on other companies
to provide you this revenue.

00:09:33.552 --> 00:09:35.260
And if you have the
right tools in place,

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:37.177
you have the flexibility
of testing, changing,

00:09:37.177 --> 00:09:38.520
and optimizing your game.

00:09:41.752 --> 00:09:43.210
So for those of
you who are looking

00:09:43.210 --> 00:09:44.918
to diversify with IAP
for the first time,

00:09:44.918 --> 00:09:46.378
really double down on that.

00:09:46.378 --> 00:09:47.920
That's a basic
framework for you that

00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:49.840
can help you in this process.

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:52.340
So first of all, you need to
think about game economy design

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:54.850
very early on in the development
process, because it's

00:09:54.850 --> 00:09:56.080
part of a core gameplay loop.

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:58.010
So don't forget that.

00:09:58.010 --> 00:10:00.490
Then think how to convert
users to be paying users,

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:03.550
or how to create the value for
money perception in your game.

00:10:03.550 --> 00:10:05.800
And lastly, you need to think
how to retain your users

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:07.540
and repeat the purchase events.

00:10:07.540 --> 00:10:09.962
Basically shifting the
focus from a one time event,

00:10:09.962 --> 00:10:11.920
a game launch, to treat
your game as a service.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:16.990
And we asked Yodo1, to
[INAUDIBLE] publisher,

00:10:16.990 --> 00:10:19.390
to share with us some
insights on this framework.

00:10:19.390 --> 00:10:21.140
And the reason we asked
Yodo1 is that they

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:23.760
have an amazing story.

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:25.970
They're also known for
hyper casual games.

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:28.222
And they have a leading
title, "Rodeo Stampede."

00:10:28.222 --> 00:10:29.805
How many of you know
"Rodeo Stampede?"

00:10:29.805 --> 00:10:30.960
It's a pretty known game.

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:31.460
Yeah.

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:32.280
OK.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:34.920
And they decided to double
down IAP in that game.

00:10:34.920 --> 00:10:36.600
In less than a
year, they managed

00:10:36.600 --> 00:10:39.050
to shift the ads to
IAP ratio in the game.

00:10:39.050 --> 00:10:41.190
So IAP today, 60%
of the revenue.

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:43.650
And only a couple of
months ago, it was 30%.

00:10:43.650 --> 00:10:45.150
And they shared
with us some insight

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:48.510
that can help you also
to think about IAP.

00:10:48.510 --> 00:10:51.480
So first of all, you need
to keep your design very

00:10:51.480 --> 00:10:54.240
simple at first, because
then you can add more layers,

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:56.157
and change that
quite easy later on.

00:10:56.157 --> 00:10:57.740
But at the same time,
try and monetize

00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:00.377
as much users as you can by
using different currencies.

00:11:00.377 --> 00:11:02.460
So they're using an ad
currency in the game world,

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:04.200
and also an IP
currency that targets

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:07.230
different type of users.

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:09.480
And they found out that in
order to convert more users

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:11.220
to be paying users,
it's really valuable

00:11:11.220 --> 00:11:13.360
to understand what is
unique about each segment,

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:14.985
and what excites them
in the game, what

00:11:14.985 --> 00:11:17.610
does staying and playing a
longer session in the game?

00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:20.250
Because then you can create
targeted offerings, which

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:21.915
makes sense for each segment.

00:11:24.413 --> 00:11:26.830
And last, it's really important
to invest in more content,

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:28.970
either by deepening the
content you already have--

00:11:28.970 --> 00:11:31.210
so if you have characters,
add more of them--

00:11:31.210 --> 00:11:33.800
or by adding more system
and features to the game.

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:36.040
In order to create a live
ops plan, with many events

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:37.540
and promotions,
it's really valuable

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:39.627
to have a system that
you can customize,

00:11:39.627 --> 00:11:41.710
because then you don't
need to invest so much time

00:11:41.710 --> 00:11:43.543
and effort in each
event, in each promotion.

00:11:43.543 --> 00:11:45.430
And you can do much
more with much less.

