00:14:31.600 --> 00:14:34.480
So can you share with the crowd
a little bit why you did it,

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:36.470
what were the reasons
behind that decision,

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:37.902
and when did it happen?

00:14:37.902 --> 00:14:38.860
EREN YANIK: Sure thing.

00:14:38.860 --> 00:14:44.270
So ads business is,
I mean, in my view,

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:47.440
it's very useful if
you're one of the two.

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:51.280
Like you're either a small
company, small studio,

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:54.430
with people that
focus on quick games,

00:14:54.430 --> 00:14:56.950
smaller games,
launching them fast,

00:14:56.950 --> 00:14:59.530
like the initial stage
that we used to be.

00:14:59.530 --> 00:15:03.670
Or if you are a publisher
that can really churn out,

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:05.290
can really produce
games really fast,

00:15:05.290 --> 00:15:07.480
like one game a
week or something,

00:15:07.480 --> 00:15:11.360
and you can rely on publishing,
other studios to help you.

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:14.410
But if you're somewhere
in the middle,

00:15:14.410 --> 00:15:18.160
probably focusing on
one game or a few games,

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:21.370
and focusing on a more
stable revenue source

00:15:21.370 --> 00:15:24.970
that is not affected
seasonally, or that does not

00:15:24.970 --> 00:15:28.780
rely on other intermediaries
between yourselves and players.

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:31.000
Because ad revenues,
you can't really

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.060
control what ads people see.

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:37.330
You can't really control the
volatility on the ad revenues.

00:15:37.330 --> 00:15:42.580
So you can only manage it by
increasing your number of games

00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:44.060
as the business grows.

00:15:44.060 --> 00:15:48.470
So that was the core reason
why we wanted to switch.

00:15:48.470 --> 00:15:50.570
And we have used
our Merge Mechanic

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.450
that we developed
in other games,

00:15:52.450 --> 00:15:53.920
like "Merged" and "Merge Town."

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:55.630
And we used it in
our "Merge Dragons."

00:15:55.630 --> 00:15:58.400
It was the core of the game.

00:15:58.400 --> 00:15:59.980
But we've used it.

00:15:59.980 --> 00:16:02.860
We merged it with a camp
so that people actually

00:16:02.860 --> 00:16:05.980
have items that
they've merged up,

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:09.350
and items that they
actually wanted to keep.

00:16:09.350 --> 00:16:12.670
So has then turned into a
higher retention, higher

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:17.877
engagement, higher
output game eventually.

00:16:17.877 --> 00:16:19.960
ADI HADDAD: And when did
it happen, that decision?

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:23.380
EREN YANIK: So this was
around early last year.

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:27.910
This was around actually
end of 2016 probably.

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:30.520
So at that point, we had
three casual hyper games.

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:33.070
And we had realized that
every new game actually

00:16:33.070 --> 00:16:35.830
boosted your revenue, but
the exponential growth

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:36.560
was not there.

00:16:36.560 --> 00:16:38.830
It was almost more linear.

00:16:38.830 --> 00:16:40.390
So what happened
was we decided to go

00:16:40.390 --> 00:16:42.280
to the next stage
we need to have

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:43.630
a game on top grossing charts.

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:47.808
We need to have a game that
has a stable number of DAU,

00:16:47.808 --> 00:16:49.600
people that you acquire
and stick with you.

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:51.520
It's not like the
leech bucket example.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:54.070
Like people actually go
in and then they leave.

00:16:54.070 --> 00:16:57.400
We wanted the more longer
term engagement with them.

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:03.920
And then we have decided to open
