00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:48.340
So from then on,
constantly iterated

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:50.830
the game, added new features.

00:17:50.830 --> 00:17:53.170
Even today, I think
the LTV is probably

00:17:53.170 --> 00:17:56.530
three times what it used to
be when we first launched it.

00:17:56.530 --> 00:17:57.940
ADI HADDAD: So
other than opening

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:00.610
an office in London, what
were the next steps following

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:01.383
that decision.

00:18:01.383 --> 00:18:03.050
What did you need to
change the company?

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:06.530
What did you need to
start from scratch?

00:18:06.530 --> 00:18:08.050
EREN YANIK: I mean,
at that point,

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:10.690
so we knew what we were good at.

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:14.920
And we knew what we required
to also improve on our side.

00:18:14.920 --> 00:18:19.750
Like we were people, Gram
Games, with the exception of me,

00:18:19.750 --> 00:18:23.760
is a very developer
oriented management base.

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:27.330
So I think we were very good
in like going to the code.

00:18:27.330 --> 00:18:29.283
Let's work on this
for two nights, then

00:18:29.283 --> 00:18:30.200
get it out of the way.

00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:31.660
Let's just have
like four Red Bulls

00:18:31.660 --> 00:18:34.470
and then do this
type of a mindset.

00:18:34.470 --> 00:18:40.510
But I think we did not have
the ideas about the business

00:18:40.510 --> 00:18:44.120
management, the layers, and the
typical performance management.

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:46.630
So up until that
point, we said, let's

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:49.630
keep the culture we built.
Let's keep the good things

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:52.267
about having a startup mindset.

00:18:52.267 --> 00:18:54.850
And it's the type of people that
when something stops working,

00:18:54.850 --> 00:18:56.960
they always open it up
and see, what's wrong?

00:18:56.960 --> 00:18:57.820
Like tinkering.

00:18:57.820 --> 00:19:00.440
Like always going
into the details.

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:03.010
So we tried to get people who
shared this vision, shared

00:19:03.010 --> 00:19:06.430
this mindset, but with people
who also have done this

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:07.820
previously with the IAP games.

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:10.580
So not to reinvent the
wheel, so to speak.

00:19:10.580 --> 00:19:13.210
So that's what we
tried to bring in.

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:18.310
And we also brought maybe about
10 people from our Istanbul

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:22.810
studio to London, and then hired
around 20 more people directly

00:19:22.810 --> 00:19:23.750
to our London office.

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:25.840
But these people
are people who have

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:27.730
worked on level
designers, people who have

00:19:27.730 --> 00:19:29.710
worked on character designs.

00:19:29.710 --> 00:19:32.610
For an IAP game, these
things really matter.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:35.260
In a hyper casual, I
think, the core thing

00:19:35.260 --> 00:19:37.450
is, do you give enough
feedback to the players,

00:19:37.450 --> 00:19:39.370
or is it really enough
differentiation?

00:19:39.370 --> 00:19:41.920
But you don't
really focus on when

00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:44.170
you level up does the
character get very different?

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:46.530
Or you don't really focus
on a longer term engagement.

00:19:46.530 --> 00:19:51.190
But you focus on your
retention metrics, like D1, D7.

00:19:51.190 --> 00:19:52.990
So we hired people
with this expertise

00:19:52.990 --> 00:19:56.800
and combined them, while
trying to maintain our company

00:19:56.800 --> 00:19:57.310
culture.

00:19:57.310 --> 00:20:00.370
And it seemed to
work well I guess.

00:20:00.370 --> 00:20:02.560
ADI HADDAD: And can you
share a little bit more

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:06.490
about what exactly is different
in developing an IAP based game

00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:08.020
compared to an ad based game?

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:11.390
What kind of metrics do you
look at when you do that?

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:17.410
EREN YANIK: I think it almost
feels to us, like an IAP

00:20:17.410 --> 00:20:23.170
game feels closer to
making a movie than almost

00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:24.450
making a hyper casual game.

00:20:24.450 --> 00:20:26.920
I mean, it's a very
extreme example.

00:20:26.920 --> 00:20:32.420
But we made "1010"
in actually 10 hours.

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:34.450
So it was a hyper casual game.

00:20:34.450 --> 00:20:37.600
But I think it literally
took like a Thursday

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:40.900
morning, an idea, and by
Thursday evening the game

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:41.480
was ready.

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:42.480
We put it on the market.

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:45.490
We saw good numbers, and
then we launched the game.

00:20:45.490 --> 00:20:47.920
But IAP is a different story.

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:52.840
Because you don't
really make your money

00:20:52.840 --> 00:20:54.280
based on your averages.

00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:57.070
You make money
based on your tail.

00:20:57.070 --> 00:20:59.740
What that means is on
a hyper casual game,

00:20:59.740 --> 00:21:02.710
you actually see D1
retention, D7 retention.

00:21:02.710 --> 00:21:06.520
What's our average revenue
per our user per day?

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:09.190
Whereas in an IAP game,
at the end of the day

00:21:09.190 --> 00:21:12.420
you focus on the top 5% of
your most engaged players.

00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:16.090
So your average
player is not directly

00:21:16.090 --> 00:21:18.210
correlated with your
average revenue.

00:21:18.210 --> 00:21:21.030
So you actually care
about your top 5%,

00:21:21.030 --> 00:21:22.950
top 10% of your engaged players.

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:24.700
How is their experience?

00:21:24.700 --> 00:21:26.280
So comments matter more.

00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:27.510
Ratings matter more.

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:29.550
Communities matter more.

00:21:29.550 --> 00:21:30.450
All of these things.

00:21:30.450 --> 00:21:33.540
Like one rating
or one review you

00:21:33.540 --> 00:21:38.290
read somewhere could have really
extensive implications for you.

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:41.070
So that's why you need
to be very much more,

00:21:41.070 --> 00:21:43.150
I think, almost iterative.

00:21:43.150 --> 00:21:46.740
In a hyper casual game
it's almost like trading,

00:21:46.740 --> 00:21:49.230
like you acquire users.

00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:50.800
They play the game
for a few days.

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:51.300
They leave.

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:52.950
And then you watch that.

00:21:52.950 --> 00:21:57.300
Whereas in an IAP game with
a higher long term retention,

00:21:57.300 --> 00:22:00.180
it becomes like an
overall experience almost.

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:03.840
Like how is this person
now on their day 35?

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:06.540
What type of dragons they
see, what type of items

00:22:06.540 --> 00:22:07.980
they interact with?

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:11.070
We always have like our
junior, mid, high level

00:22:11.070 --> 00:22:13.800
player, where they're at
when they're experienced,

00:22:13.800 --> 00:22:16.643
how much more time are
they expected to spend?

00:22:16.643 --> 00:22:18.060
What is their level
of engagement?

00:22:18.060 --> 00:22:19.020
How is that varying?

00:22:19.020 --> 00:22:22.200
So those things
are very different.

00:22:22.200 --> 00:22:25.500
What we tried to bring them
in from our past experience

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:28.110
with hyper casual games
is, it's very hard

00:22:28.110 --> 00:22:30.440
to launch an IAP game fast.

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:33.370
And we're not still
perfect at it.

00:22:33.370 --> 00:22:36.330
But what you can do
is you could take

00:22:36.330 --> 00:22:38.220
certain loops and
certain mechanics

00:22:38.220 --> 00:22:42.110
that you know that work,
put them out first, and then

00:22:42.110 --> 00:22:43.980
D1, D7, see how they do.

00:22:43.980 --> 00:22:48.660
Like set more
intermediary expectations,

00:22:48.660 --> 00:22:51.900
KPIs on what you
think you should have.

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:53.990
And only then, act on it.

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:56.190
That, for us, is the similarity.

00:22:56.190 --> 00:23:01.020
But the core difference is more
about engagement rather than

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:01.870
averages.

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:02.495
ADI HADDAD: OK.

00:23:02.495 --> 00:23:05.168
And in retrospect, other than
the acquisition by Zynga,

00:23:05.168 --> 00:23:06.960
were you happy with
what happened following

00:23:06.960 --> 00:23:08.578
the launch of "Merge Dragons?"

00:23:08.578 --> 00:23:09.870
EREN YANIK: We were very happy.

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:18.210
And I think even
internally, you share things

00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:20.310
at a different level
with your players

00:23:20.310 --> 00:23:23.370
when it's a more immersive game.

00:23:23.370 --> 00:23:26.760
Because I don't how many people
here played "1010" or "Six!",

00:23:26.760 --> 00:23:29.970
but those are the games
that you don't feel--

00:23:29.970 --> 00:23:33.090
like you're never like
a crazy "1010" fan.

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:36.420
